<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Cameron, Duncan. A sketch of the Customs, Manners, and Way of Living of the Natives, All the Quadrupeds, as Well as Birds, and Fishes, that are Found in the barren Country About Nipigon, <span class="AddHand-editors">[1804]</span>. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0026</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">are never at a loss to find one another: their method of doing this, is as follows; &#8211; one of them will take a piece of Birch Rind, and with coal, or the point of his knife, design his Totem, his wife's, and that of any other persons or persons in company, so many Males and so many females of such Tribes, designing each in proportion to his size &#8211; the wife never takes the Husbands mark, but retains that of the family to which she belonged &#8211; it follows of course that the children of both sexes always take the Father's mark.  Whenever they leave any of these marks, they fasten them to a pole, pointing to the way they are going; and if <span class="AddHand-author">in</span> summer will leave a bunch of green leaves, that from their size or withered state, you may give a pretty good conjecture at what time they passed &#8211; and if any of the family died lately, he is designed without a head, or laying on his side &#8211; they write songs for one another likewise, by designing the Animals, Birds, or</p>

